<h5>4 Collaborating on a mural</h5>
<audio id="audio-814-4" class="wp-audio-shortcode" style="width: 100%; visibility: hidden;" preload="none" controls="controls"><source type="audio/mpeg" src="http://www.dandavies23.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/4-Working-in-a-collaborative-mural.mp3?_=4" /><a href="http://www.dandavies23.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/4-Working-in-a-collaborative-mural.mp3">http://www.dandavies23.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/4-Working-in-a-collaborative-mural.mp3</a></audio>

</aside>
<div id="aesop-image-component-814-9" class="aesop-component aesop-image-component ">
<div class="aesop-content">
<figure class="aesop-image-component-image aesop-component-align-left aesop-image-component-caption-left" style="max-width: 100%;"><img src="http://www.dandavies23.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/2015-09-07-14.42.01.jpg" alt="2015-09-07-14.42.01" /></figure>
</div>
</div>
Bergner’s message is that his work isn’t done from a sense of guilt. His advice to help in a situation like this is to look to your own passions and strengths.

